\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Technical writeup\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 HOW I BUILT IT
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 From movie metadata to semantic cartography.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The finished map looks simple: dots, territories, labels, search, and nearest neighbors. The hard part was making those pieces mean the same thing.\
This project became less about drawing a pretty embedding and more about building a trustworthy semantic geography: a system where the data model, labels, borders, and user interface all describe the same underlying structure.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 01\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Start with a defensible data story\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The first version used the official TMDb API to build controlled movie profiles from titles, overviews, genres, keywords, and short review-language snippets.\
That made the project viable as a public portfolio piece: no Letterboxd scraping, no IMDb review scraping, no private datasets, and no raw review text exposed in the browser.\
But the early profiles were too thin. They produced some good neighbors, but not enough depth for the kind of \'93vibe map\'94 the interface wanted.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 02\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Build semantic profiles, not keyword soup\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The stronger version combined multiple public signals: TMDb metadata, MovieLens Tag Genome relevance scores, MPST plot tags and synopses, controlled synopsis texture, and light review language.\
The key lesson was that 
\f1\b more text was not automatically better
\f0\b0 . Heavy review text added noise. Title-heavy profiles created leakage. The best representation balanced plot, theme, tone, audience perception, and genre without letting any single source dominate.\
Each film became a semantic profile: a compact description of what the movie is about, how it feels, and what viewers tend to associate with it.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 03\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Keep similarity in the full embedding space\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Each semantic profile was embedded into a high-dimensional vector. Nearest neighbors are calculated there, where the semantic signal is strongest.\
The visible map is a projection. It is useful for exploration, but it is not treated as the source of truth.\
That distinction mattered. A raw 2D projection can make good semantic neighbors appear far apart, or make nearby dots look more related than they really are. The atlas needed to be visually readable without pretending that screen distance explains everything.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 04\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Make the hierarchy real\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The biggest early failure was structural.\
Macro regions, neighborhoods, and microclusters originally behaved like separate layers that looked nested in the UI but were not always truly nested in the data.\
The final system uses strict hierarchical clustering:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
cluster the full set into macro regions\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
cluster within each macro region into neighborhoods\
\ls1\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
cluster within each neighborhood into microclusters\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 That means every film has one real path through the atlas:\

\f1\b macro region 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  neighborhood 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  microcluster
\f0\b0 \
The geography is not just a visual effect. It is enforced by the data model.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 05\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Make labels poetic but accountable\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The labels are the product surface. They are how people understand the map.\
I used LLM-assisted labeling to generate names for regions, neighborhoods, and microclusters, but the goal was not to blindly accept whatever sounded clever. Labels had to be vivid enough to feel human and specific enough to be useful.\
The guiding phrase became:\

\f1\b poetic but accountable
\f0\b0 \
A good label should be memorable, but it should also be supported by representative films, tags, cluster evidence, and nearest-neighbor behavior.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 06\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Turn the frontend into a QA surface\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The interface exposed problems the pipeline alone could hide.\
Some labels overpromised. Some borders implied relationships that were not true. Some nearest neighbors were semantically good but visually surprising. Some map experiments looked beautiful but were less honest.\
Search, selected-film panels, expandable cluster cards, and nearest-neighbor links became more than UI features. They became audit tools.\
The frontend became a cartography problem: how do you show high-dimensional semantic relationships in a way that feels readable, stable, and honest?\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Static export\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 STATIC EXPORT
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 The public site ships the atlas, not the pipeline.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The final site is static. A sanitized JSON export gives the Astro page enough movie metadata, cluster labels, map positions, territory geometry, and nearest-neighbor lists to render the atlas entirely in the browser.\
There is no backend required for the public experience.\
The browser does not expose API keys, call the data pipeline, or ship raw reviews or embedding vectors. Raw source responses, review text, embeddings, and experiment artifacts stay out of the public export.\
\

\f2 \uc0\u11835 
\f0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Validation loop\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 VALIDATION LOOP
\f0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 Subjective quality became measurable enough to improve.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 A semantic map is partly subjective, so validation could not be purely mathematical. I used a mix of known-film spot checks, cluster-label review, structural scans, large LLM-assisted audits, and targeted repairs.\
The final public export contains:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
10,000 films\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
946 labels\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
16 macro regions\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
180 neighborhoods\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
750 microclusters\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
no duplicate macro/neighborhood/micro path labels\
\ls2\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
no API keys, raw reviews, or embeddings in the browser\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The broad 10,000-film audit found 9,633 passes, 336 mixed cases, and 31 failures before targeted repair. Rechecking the failure set produced 22 passes, 9 mixed cases, and 0 failures, which supported the decision to stop broad reruns and focus only on concrete wording repairs.\
The goal was not perfect ontology. It was a trustworthy, inspectable, public-facing semantic atlas.\
\

